          <definition>
            <term>Conjugate acid-base pair</term>
            <meaning>
	      <para>A conjugate acid-base pair contains two compounds that differ only by a hydrogen ion (<chem_compound>H^{+}</chem_compound>) and a charge of <number>+1</number>.</para>
            </meaning>
          </definition>
	  <worked_example>
	    <title>Conjugate acid-base pairs</title>
	    <question>
	      <para>Determine the conjugate acid-base pairs for the following reaction:</para>
	      <para><chem_compound>HNO_{3}(aq) + OH^{-}(aq)</chem_compound> <latex>\rightleftharpoons</latex> <chem_compound>NO_{3}^{-}(aq) + H_{2}O(ℓ)</chem_compound></para>
	    </question>
	    <answer>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Which reactant is an acid and which is a base?</title>
		<para><chem_compound>HNO_{3}</chem_compound> is nitric acid. It donates a proton in the forward reaction:</para>
		<para><chem_compound>HNO_{3}(aq)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>NO_{3}^{-}(aq) + H^{+}(aq)</chem_compound></para>
		<para><chem_compound>OH^{-}</chem_compound> accepts a proton in the forward reaction and is therefore the base:</para>
		<para><chem_compound>OH^{-}(aq) + H^{+}(aq)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>H_{2}O(ℓ)</chem_compound></para>
	      </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Which product is the conjugate base of the acid?</title>
		<para>Nitric acid (<chem_compound>HNO_{3}</chem_compound>) donates a proton to become <chem_compound>NO_{3}^{-}</chem_compound>. In the reverse reaction <chem_compound>NO_{3}^{-}</chem_compound> accepts a proton to become <chem_compound>HNO_{3}</chem_compound>. Therefore <chem_compound>NO_{3}^{-}</chem_compound> is the conjugate base of <chem_compound>HNO_{3}</chem_compound>.</para>
		<para><chem_compound>NO_{3}^{-}(aq) + H^{+}(aq)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>HNO_{3}(aq)</chem_compound></para>
	      </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Which product is the conjugate acid of the base?</title>
		<para><chem_compound>OH^{-}</chem_compound> accepts a proton to become <chem_compound>H_{2}O</chem_compound>. In the reverse reaction <chem_compound>H_{2}O</chem_compound> donates a proton to become <chem_compound>OH^{-}</chem_compound>. Therefore <chem_compound>H_{2}O</chem_compound> is the conjugate acid of <chem_compound>OH^{-}</chem_compound>.</para>
		<para><chem_compound>H_{2}O(ℓ)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>OH^{-}(aq) + H^{+}(aq)</chem_compound></para>
	      </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Label the conjugate acid-base pairs in this reaction</title>
		<pspicture>
		  <code>
		    (-5.2,-2)(3.5,1)
		    \rput(-4.2,0){\textbf{HNO$_{3}$(aq)}}
		    \rput(-3.1,0){\textbf{+}}
		    \rput(-2.1,0){\textbf{OH$^{-}$(aq)}}
		    \rput(-0.95,0){\textbf{$\rightleftharpoons$}}
		    \rput(0.2,0){\textbf{NO$_{3}^{-}$(aq)}}
		    \rput(1.3,0){\textbf{+}}
		    \rput(2.3,0){\textbf{H$_{2}$O(ℓ)}}
		    \rput(-4.2,-0.6){\textbf{acid}}
		    \rput(-2.1,-0.6){\textbf{base}}
		    \rput(0.2,-0.5){\textbf{conjugate}}
		    \rput(0.2,-0.9){\textbf{base}}
		    \rput(2.3,-0.5){\textbf{conjugate}}
		    \rput(2.3,-0.9){\textbf{acid}}
		    \psline(-4.2,-1.1)(-4.2,-1.4)
		    \psline(-4.2,-1.4)(0.2,-1.4)
		    \psline(0.2,-1.4)(0.2,-1.1)
		    \rput(-2,-1.65){\textbf{conjugate pair}}
		    \psline(-2.1,0.25)(-2.1,0.5)
		    \psline(-2.1,0.5)(2.3,0.5)
		    \psline(2.3,0.5)(2.3,0.25)
		    \rput(0.1,0.75){\textbf{conjugate pair}}
		  </code>
		</pspicture>
	      </workstep>
	    </answer>
	  </worked_example>
