	<section type="subsection">
	  <title><latex>K_{a}</latex> and <latex>K_{b}</latex></title>
	  <para>The equilibrium constant for the ionisation process of an acid (the extent to which ions are formed in solution) is given by the term <latex>{\text{K}_{\textcolor{red}{\textbf{a}}}}</latex>, while that for a base is given by <latex>{\text{K}_{\textcolor{blue}{\textbf{b}}}}</latex>. These equilibrium constants are a way of determining whether the acid or base is weak or strong.</para>
	  <para>Remember from <link url="to-do-chemical-equilibrium">Chapter 8</link> that we calculate K as follows:</para>
	  <para><latex>{\text{K}} = \dfrac{\text{[products]}}{\text{[reactants]}}</latex></para>
	  <section type="subsubsection">
	    <title>Acids</title>
	    <list list-type="bulleted">
	      <item>
		<para><emphasis effect="bold">Strong acids</emphasis></para>
		<para>Consider the ionisation of <chem_compound>HBr</chem_compound>:</para>
		<para><latex>\textcolor{red}{\text{HBr(g)}}</latex> + <chem_compound>H_{2}O(ℓ)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>H_{3}O^{+}(aq) + Br^{-}(aq)</chem_compound></para>
		<para>We are calculating <latex>\textcolor{red}{\text{K}_{\text{a}}}</latex> here as it is an <latex>\textcolor{red}{\text{acid}}</latex> being dissolved in water. The <emphasis effect="italics">liquid</emphasis> water is not included in the equation.</para>
		<para><latex>\textcolor{red}{\text{K}_{\text{a}}} = \dfrac{\text{[H}_{3}{\text{O}}^{+}{\text{(aq)][Br}^{-}{\text{(aq)]}}}}{\textcolor{red}{\text{[HBr(g)]}}}</latex></para>
		<para>The value of <chem_compound>K_{a}</chem_compound> for this reaction is very high (approximately <number><coeff>1</coeff><exp>9</exp></number>). This means that there are many more moles of product than reactant. The <chem_compound>HBr</chem_compound> molecules are almost all ionised to <chem_compound>H^{+}</chem_compound> and <chem_compound>Br^{-}</chem_compound>.</para>
		<para>We can then show that in the ionisation reaction <chem_compound>HBr</chem_compound> is almost completely ionised. Effectively, any value above <number><coeff>1</coeff><exp>3</exp></number> is large and shows that almost complete ionisation has occurred:</para>
		<pspicture>
		  <code>
		    (-2,-2)(7,0.5)
		    \newrgbcolor{purple}{0.78 0.13 1}
		    \rput(0,0){\textbf{HBr${\textbf{(g) + H}}$_{2}$O{\textbf{(ℓ)}}}}
		    \psline[linecolor=purple](1.6,0.05)(3.1,0.05)
		    \psline(1.6,-0.05)(2.1,-0.05)
		    \psline[linecolor=purple](3.1,0.05)(2.8,0.15)
		    \psline(1.6,-0.05)(1.9,-0.15)
		    \rput(5,0){\textbf{H$_{3}$O$^{+}${\textbf{(aq) + Br}}$^{-}${\textbf{(aq)}}}}
		    \psline[linecolor=purple,linewidth=1pt,arrows=-&gt;,arrowlength=3,arrowsize=7pt,arrowinset=0.25](0,-0.5)(5,-0.5)
		    \rput(2.5,-0.9){\purple almost complete ionisation}
		    \rput(2.5,-1.4){\purple large percentage of molecules ionised}
		  </code>
		</pspicture>
		<para>The unequal double arrows in the reaction equation indicate that the equilibrium position favours the formation of ions. This is in contrast to the ionisation of a weak acid.</para>
	      </item>
	      <item>
		<para><emphasis effect="bold">Weak acids</emphasis></para>
		<para>Consider the ionisation of ethanoic acid (<chem_compound>CH_{3}COOH</chem_compound>):</para>
		<para><latex>\textcolor{red}{\text{CH}_{3}{\text{COOH(aq)}}}</latex> + <chem_compound>H_{2}O(ℓ)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>H_{3}O^{+}(aq) + CH_{3}COO^{-}(aq)</chem_compound></para>
		<para>Therefore, <latex>\textcolor{red}{\text{K}_{\text{a}}} = \dfrac{\text{[H}_{3}{\text{O}}^{+}{\text{(aq)][CH}}_{3}{\text{COO}}^{-}{\text{(aq)]}}}{\textcolor{red}{\text{[CH}_{3}{\text{COOH(aq)]}}}}</latex></para>
		<para>The value of <latex>\textcolor{red}{\text{K}_{\text{a}}}</latex> for this reaction is very low (approximately <number><coeff>1.7</coeff><exp>-5</exp></number>), showing that only a few of the <chem_compound>CH_{3}COOH</chem_compound> molecules ionise to form <chem_compound>H_{3}O^{+}</chem_compound> (in water) and <chem_compound>CH_{3}COO^{-}</chem_compound>.</para>
		<para>We can write the reaction with an unequal double arrow to show the position of the equilibrium, which does not favour the formation of ions:</para>
		<pspicture>
		  <code>
		    (-3.3,-2)(8.5,0.5)
		    \rput(-1,0){\textbf{CH}$_{3}${\textbf{COOH(aq) + H}}$_{2}${\textbf{O(ℓ)}}}
		    \psline[linecolor=orange](2.6,0.05)(3.1,0.05)
		    \psline(1.6,-0.05)(3.1,-0.05)
		    \psline[linecolor=orange](3.1,0.05)(2.8,0.15)
		    \psline(1.6,-0.05)(1.9,-0.15)
		    \rput(6,0){\textbf{H}$_{3}${\textbf{O}}$^{+}${\textbf{(aq) + CH}}$_{3}${\textbf{COO}}$^{-}${\textbf{(aq)}}}
		    \psline[linecolor=orange,linewidth=1pt,arrows=&gt;,arrowlength=3,arrowsize=7pt,arrowinset=0.25](3.2,-0.5)(1.8,-0.5)
		    \rput(2.5,-0.9){\orange very little ionisation}
		    \rput(2.5,-1.4){\orange small percentage of molecules ionised}
		  </code>
		</pspicture>
	      </item>
	    </list>
