	  <section type="subsubsection">
	    <title>Bases</title>
	    <para>The dissociation of bases is similar to that of acids in that we look at the <latex>\textcolor{blue}{\text{K}_{\text{b}}}</latex> values in a similar manner:</para>
	    <list list-type="bulleted">
	      <item>
		<para><emphasis effect="bold">Strong bases</emphasis></para>
		<para>For a strong base like <chem_compound>NaOH</chem_compound>:</para>
		<para><latex>\textcolor{blue}{\text{NaOH(aq)}}</latex> + <chem_compound>H_{2}O(ℓ)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>Na^{+}(aq) + OH^{-}(aq) + H_{2}O(ℓ)</chem_compound></para>
		<para><latex>\textcolor{blue}{\text{K}_{\text{b}}} = \dfrac{\text{[Na}^{+}{\text{(aq)][OH}}^{-}{\text{(aq)]}}}{\textcolor{blue}{\text{[NaOH(aq)]}}}</latex></para>
		<para>The <latex>\textcolor{blue}{\text{K}_{\text{b}}}</latex> for <chem_compound>NaOH</chem_compound> is very large (<chem_compound>NaOH</chem_compound> is a strong base and almost completely dissociates) and shows that the equilibrium lies very far to the <chem_compound>OH^{-}</chem_compound> side of the reaction. As a result we can write the equilibrium as:</para>
		<pspicture>
		  <code>
		    (-1.5,-2)(7,0.5)
		    \rput(0.5,0){\textbf{NaOH$_{\text{(aq)}}$}}
		    \psline[linecolor=purple](1.6,0.05)(3.1,0.05)
		    \psline(1.6,-0.05)(2,-0.05)
		    \psline[linecolor=purple](3.1,0.05)(2.8,0.15)
		    \psline(1.6,-0.05)(1.9,-0.15)
		    \rput(5,0){\textbf{Na$^{+}$_{\text{(aq)}}$ + OH$^{-}$_{\text{(aq)}}$}}
		    \psline[linecolor=purple,linewidth=1pt,arrows=-&gt;,arrowlength=3,arrowsize=7pt,arrowinset=0.25](0,-0.5)(5,-0.5)
		    \rput(2.5,-0.9){\purple almost complete dissociation}
		    \rput(2.5,-1.4){\purple large percentage of molecules dissociate}
		  </code>
		</pspicture>
	      </item>
	      <item>
		<para><emphasis effect="bold">Weak bases</emphasis></para>
		<para><latex>\textcolor{blue}{\text{NH}_{3}{\text{(g)}}}</latex> + <chem_compound>H_{2}O(ℓ)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>NH_{4}^{+}(aq) + OH^{-}(aq)</chem_compound></para>
		<para><latex>\textcolor{blue}{\text{K}_{\text{b}}} = \dfrac{\text{[NH}_{4}^{+}{\text{(aq)][OH}}^{-}{\text{(aq)]}}}{\textcolor{blue}{\text{[NH}_{3}{\text{(g)]}}}}</latex></para>
		<para>The <latex>\textcolor{blue}{\text{K}_{\text{b}}}</latex> for <chem_compound>NH_{3}</chem_compound> is approximately <number><coeff>1.8</coeff><exp>-5</exp></number> (<chem_compound>NH_{3}</chem_compound> is a weak base) and shows that the equilibrium lies to the <chem_compound>NH_{3}</chem_compound> side of the reaction. As a result we can write the equilibrium as:</para>
		<pspicture>
		  <code>
		    (-1.7,-2)(7.5,0.5)
		    \rput(-0.2,0){\textbf{NH$_{3}{\text{(g) + H}}$_{2}${\text{O(ℓ)}}}}
		    \psline[linecolor=orange](2.6,0.05)(3.1,0.05)
		    \psline(1.6,-0.05)(3.1,-0.05)
		    \psline[linecolor=orange](3.1,0.05)(2.8,0.15)
		    \psline(1.6,-0.05)(1.9,-0.15)
		    \rput(5.3,0){\textbf{NH$_{4}$^{+}${\text{(aq) + OH}}$^{-}${\text{(aq)}}}}
		    \psline[linecolor=orange,linewidth=1pt,arrows=&gt;,arrowlength=3,arrowsize=7pt,arrowinset=0.25](3.2,-0.5)(1.8,-0.5)
		    \rput(2.5,-0.9){\orange very little ionisation}
		    \rput(2.5,-1.4){\orange small percentage of molecules ionised}
		  </code>
		</pspicture>
	      </item>
	    </list>
	  </section>
	  <worked_example>
	    <title>Equilibrium constant calculations</title>
	    <question>
	      <para>Calculate the equilibrium constant for hydrochloric acid added to <unit_number><number>1.38</number><unit>dm<sup>3</sup></unit></unit_number> of water:</para>
	      <para><chem_compound>HCl(aq) + H_{2}O(ℓ)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>H_{3}O^{+}(aq) + Cl^{-}(aq)</chem_compound></para>
	      <para>n(<chem_compound>HCl</chem_compound>) in solution = <unit_number><number>0.005</number><unit>mol</unit></unit_number></para>
	      <para>n(<chem_compound>Cl^{-}</chem_compound>) in solution = <unit_number><number>87.3</number><unit>mol</unit></unit_number></para>
	    </question>
	    <answer>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Calculate the concentration of <chem_compound>HCl</chem_compound> at equilibrium</title>
		<para>C(<chem_compound>HCl</chem_compound>) <latex>= \dfrac{\text{n}}{\text{V}} = \dfrac{<number>0.005</number> {\text{ mol}}}{<number>1.38</number> {\text{ dm}}^{3}}</latex> = <unit_number><number>0.0036</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number></para>
	      </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Calculate the concentration of <chem_compound>Cl^{-}</chem_compound> at equilibrium</title>
		<para>C(<chem_compound>Cl^{-}</chem_compound>) <latex>= \dfrac{\text{n}}{\text{V}} = \dfrac{<number>87.3</number> {\text{ mol}}}{<number>1.38</number> {\text{ dm}}^{3}}</latex> = <unit_number><number>63.3</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number></para>
	      </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Calculate the concentration of <chem_compound>H_{3}O^{+}</chem_compound> at equilibrium</title>
		<para>There is a <number>1</number>:<number>1</number> mole ratio between <chem_compound>H_{3}O^{+}</chem_compound> and <chem_compound>Cl^{-}</chem_compound>. Therefore, if <unit_number><number>87.3</number><unit>mol</unit></unit_number> of <chem_compound>Cl^{-}</chem_compound> is present at equilibrium, <unit_number><number>87.3</number><unit>mol</unit></unit_number> of <chem_compound>H_{3}O^{+}</chem_compound> must be present as well.</para>
		<para>C(<chem_compound>H_{3}O^{+}</chem_compound>) <latex>= \dfrac{\text{n}}{\text{V}} = \dfrac{<number>87.3</number> {\text{ mol}}}{<number>1.38</number> {\text{ dm}}^{3}}</latex> = <unit_number><number>63.3</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number></para>
	      </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Calculate <chem_compound>K_{a}</chem_compound> (because <chem_compound>HCl</chem_compound> is an acid)</title>
		<para><latex>\text{K}_{\text{a}} = \dfrac{\text{[H}_{3}{\text{O}}^{+}{\text{(aq)]}}^{1}{\text{[Cl}}^{-}{\text{(aq)]}}^{1}}{\text{[HCl]}^{1}}</latex></para>
		<para><latex>\text{K}_{\text{a}} = \dfrac{<number>63.3</number> \times <number>63.3</number>}{<number>0.0036</number>}</latex> = <number><coeff>1.11</coeff><exp>6</exp></number></para>
	      </workstep>
	    </answer>
	  </worked_example>
	  <note type="tip">
	    <para>In a balanced chemical equation such as:</para>
	    <para><chem_compound>2C</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>A + B</chem_compound></para>
	    <para><chem_compound>K_{a}</chem_compound> = <latex>\dfrac{\text{[A]}^{1}\text{[B]}^{1}}{\text{[C]}^{2}}</latex></para>
	    <para>However, we generally do not include the superscripts when the coefficients in the balanced equation are <emphasis effect="bold">1</emphasis>:</para>
	    <para><chem_compound>K_{a}</chem_compound> = <latex>\dfrac{\text{[A][B]}}{\text{[C]}^{2}}</latex></para>
	    <para>Remember that <chem_compound>x^{1}</chem_compound> = x.</para>
	  </note>
	  <worked_example>
	    <title>Equilibrium constant calculations</title>
	    <question>
	      <para>The equilibrium constant (<chem_compound>K_{b}</chem_compound>) for the following reaction is <number><coeff>1.8</coeff><exp>-5</exp></number>.</para>
	      <para><chem_compound>NH_{3}(aq) + H_{2}O(ℓ)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>NH_{4}^{+}(aq) + OH^{-}(aq)</chem_compound></para>
	      <para>Calculate the mass (at equilibrium) of <chem_compound>NH_{3}</chem_compound> molecules dissolved in <unit_number><number>4</number><unit>dm<sup>3</sup></unit></unit_number> of water if there is a <unit_number><number>0.00175</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number> concentration of hydroxide ions at equilibrium.</para>
	    </question>
	    <answer>
	      <workstep>
		<title>What is the <chem_compound>K_{b}</chem_compound> equation for this reaction</title>
		<para><latex>\text{K}_{\text{b}} = \dfrac{{\text{[NH}}_{4}^{+}{\text{(aq)]}}^{1}{\text{[OH}}^{-}{\text{(aq)]}}^{1}}{{\text{[NH}}_{3}{\text{(aq)]}}^{1}}</latex></para>
	      </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Calculate the concentration of <chem_compound>NH_{3}</chem_compound> at equilibrium</title>
		<para>If there is a <unit_number><number>0.00175</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number> concentration of <chem_compound>OH^{-}</chem_compound> ions at equilibrium there must be an equal concentration of <chem_compound>NH_{4}^{+}</chem_compound> ions.</para>
		<para><latex>\text{[NH}_{3}{\text{(aq)]}} = \dfrac{{\text{[NH}}_{4}^{+}{\text{(aq)]}}^{1}{\text{[OH}}^{-}{\text{(aq)]}}^{1}}{{\text{K}}_{\text{b}}} = \dfrac{{\text{(}}<number>0.00175</number>{\text{)}}{\text{(}}<number>0.00175</number>{\text{)}}}{<number><coeff>1.8</coeff><exp>-5</exp></number>} = </latex> <unit_number><number>0.17</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number></para>
	      </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Calculate the number of moles of <chem_compound>NH_{3}</chem_compound> at equilibrium</title>
		<para><latex>\text{C (mol.dm}^{-3}{\text{)}} = \dfrac{\text{n (mol)}}{\text{V (dm}^{3}{\text{)}}}</latex>, therefore:</para>
		<para>n = C x V = <unit_number><number>0.17</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number> x <unit_number><number>4</number><unit>dm<sup>3</sup></unit></unit_number> = <unit_number><number>0.68</number><unit>mol</unit></unit_number></para>
	      </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Calculate the mass of <chem_compound>NH_{3}</chem_compound> in solution at equilibrium</title>
		<para><latex>\text{n (mol)} = \dfrac{\text{m (g)}}{\text{M (g.mol}^{-1}{\text{)}}}</latex>. Therefore m = n x M</para>
		<para>M(<chem_compound>NH_{3}</chem_compound>) = <number>14.0</number> + (<number>3</number> x <number>1.01</number>) = <unit_number><number>17.03</number><unit>g.mol<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number></para>
		<para>m = <unit_number><number>0.68</number><unit>mol</unit></unit_number> x <unit_number><number>17.03</number><unit>g.mol<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number> = <unit_number><number>11.6</number><unit>g</unit></unit_number></para>
	      </workstep>
	    </answer>
	  </worked_example>
	</section>
