		<para>A dilute acid is added to a metal hydroxide to form a salt and water. The salt is formed by the metal cation and the anion from the acid. In this reaction the metal hydroxide is acting as a base. For example:</para>
		<para><latex>\textcolor{red}{\text{hydrochloric acid}} + \textcolor{blue}{\text{zinc hydroxide}} \to \textcolor{blue}{\text{zinc}} \textcolor{red}{\text{ chloride}}</latex> + water</para>
		<para><chem_compound>2HCl(aq) + Zn(OH)_{2}(s)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>ZnCl_{2}(aq) + 2H_{2}O(ℓ)</chem_compound></para>
	      </item>
	      <item>
		<para><emphasis effect="bold">Acid + metal oxide</emphasis> <latex>\to</latex> <emphasis effect="bold">salt + water</emphasis></para>
		<para>A dilute acid is added to a metal oxide to form a salt and water. The salt is formed by the metal cation and the anion from the acid. In this reaction the metal oxide is acting as a base. For example:</para>
		<para><latex>\textcolor{red}{\text{hydrochloric acid}} + \textcolor{blue}{\text{zinc oxide}} \to \textcolor{blue}{\text{zinc}} \textcolor{red}{\text{ chloride}}</latex> + water</para>
		<para><chem_compound>2HCl(aq) + ZnO(s)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>ZnCl_{2}(aq) + H_{2}O(ℓ)</chem_compound></para>
	      </item>
	      <item>
		<para><emphasis effect="bold">Acid + metal carbonate</emphasis> <latex>\to</latex> <emphasis effect="bold">salt + water + carbon dioxide</emphasis></para>
		<para>A dilute acid is added to a metal carbonate to form a salt, water and carbon dioxide gas. The salt is formed by the metal cation and the anion from the acid. In this reaction the metal carbonate is acting as a base. For example:</para>
		<para><latex>\textcolor{red}{\text{hydrochloric acid}} + \textcolor{blue}{\text{zinc carbonate}} \to \textcolor{blue}{\text{zinc}} \textcolor{red}{\text{ chloride}}</latex> + water + carbon dioxide</para>
		<para><chem_compound>2HCl(aq) + ZnCO_{3}(s)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>ZnCl_{2}(aq) + H_{2}O(ℓ) + CO_{2}(g)</chem_compound></para>
	      </item>
	      <item>
		<para><emphasis effect="bold">Acid + metal hydrogen carbonate</emphasis> <latex>\to</latex> <emphasis effect="bold">salt + water + carbon dioxide</emphasis></para>
		<para>A dilute acid is added to a metal hydrogen carbonate to form a salt, water and carbon dioxide gas. The salt is formed by the metal cation and the anion from the acid. In this reaction the metal hydrogen carbonate is acting as a base. For example:</para>
		<para><latex>\textcolor{red}{\text{hydrochloric acid}} + \textcolor{blue}{\text{zinc bicarbonate}} \to \textcolor{blue}{\text{zinc}} \textcolor{red}{\text{ chloride}}</latex> + water + carbon dioxide</para>
		<para><chem_compound>2HCl(aq) + Zn(HCO_{3})_{2}(s)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>>ZnCl_{2}(aq) + 2H_{2}O(ℓ) + 2CO_{2}(g)</chem_compound></para>
	      </item>
	    </list>
	  </teachers-guide>
