	  <worked_example>
	    <title>Determining equations from starting materials</title>
	    <question>
	      <para>Hydroiodic acid (<chem_compound>HI</chem_compound>) is added to solid potassium hydroxide (<chem_compound>KOH</chem_compound>). Give the balanced chemical equation for this reaction.</para>
	    </question>
	    <answer>
	      <workstep>
		<title>What are the reactants?</title>
		<para>An acid (<chem_compound>HI</chem_compound>) and a base (<chem_compound>KOH</chem_compound>).</para>
	      </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>What will the products be?</title>
		<para>As this is the reaction of an acid and base (which contains a hydroxide anion) the products will be a salt and water.</para>
		<para>hydroiodic acid + potassium hydroxide <latex>\to</latex> salt + water</para>
	      </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>What is the formula of the salt?</title>
		<para>The cation will come from the base (<chem_compound>K^{+}</chem_compound>). The anion will come from the acid (<chem_compound>I^{-}</chem_compound>). Due to the charges on the cation and anion there must be one <chem_compound>K^{+}</chem_compound> for every one <chem_compound>I^{-}</chem_compound>.</para>
		<para>Therefore the formula for the salt will be: <chem_compound>KI</chem_compound>.</para>
	      </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Write the equation for this reaction</title>
		<para><chem_compound>HI(aq) + KOH(s)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>KI(aq) + H_{2}O(ℓ)</chem_compound></para>
		<para>This can also be written:</para>
		<para><chem_compound>HI(aq) + KOH(s)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>K^{+}(aq) + I^{-}(aq) + H_{2}O(ℓ)</chem_compound></para>
	      </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Make sure that the equation is balanced</title>
		<para>The equation is balanced.</para>
	      </workstep>
	    </answer>
	  </worked_example>
