    <section type="subsection">
      <title>Indicators</title>
      <shortcode>Shortcode</shortcode>
      <para>A titration is a process for determining, with precision, the concentration of a solution with unknown concentration. The theory behind titrations will be discussed later in this chapter. An indicator is used to show the scientist carrying out the reaction exactly when the reaction has reached completion.</para>
      <teachers-guide>
	<para>This experiment looks at the change in colour of an indicator during an acid-base reaction. It is effectively a very rough titration experiment. Principles that can be applied to titrations, such as adding a small volume of acid, then swirling, can be applied here as well. It is important that the learners understand that the pH range that the indicator changes colour in is not always around <number>7</number>.</para>
	<para>Learners are working with a strong acid and a strong base in this reaction. Concentrated, strong acids and bases can cause serious burns. Please remind the learners to be careful and wear the appropriate safety equipment when handling all chemicals, especially concentrated acids and bases. The safety equipment includes gloves, safety glasses, and protective clothing.</para>
      </teachers-guide>
      <activity type="g_experiment">
