	    <problem>
	      <para>Calculate the number of moles of <chem_compound>NaHCO_{3}</chem_compound> used to bake the cake.</para>
	    </problem>
	    <solution>
	      <para>M(<chem_compound>NaHCO_{3}</chem_compound>) = <number>23.0</number> + <number>1.01</number> + <number>12.0</number> + (<number>3</number> x <number>16.0</number>) = <unit_number><number>84.01</number><unit>g.mol<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number></para>
	      <para>n(<chem_compound>NaHCO_{3}</chem_compound>) = <latex>\dfrac{\text{m}}{\text{M}} = \dfrac{<unit_number><number>1.6</number><unit>g</unit></unit_number>}{<unit_number><number>84.01</number><unit>g.mol<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number>} = </latex><correct><unit_number><number>0.019</number><unit>mol</unit></unit_number></correct></para>	
	    </solution>
	  </entry>
	  <entry>
	    <problem>
	      <para>How many atoms of oxygen are there in <unit_number><number>1.6</number><unit>g</unit></unit_number> of baking soda?</para>
	    </problem>
	    <solution>
	      <para><chem_compound>N_{A}</chem_compound> (Avogadro's number) = <unit_number><number><coeff>6.022</coeff><exp>23</exp></number><unit>atoms.mol<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number>.</para>
	      <para>Number of atoms = n x <chem_compound>N_{A}</chem_compound> = <unit_number><number>0.019</number><unit>mol</unit></unit_number> x <unit_number><number><coeff>6.022</coeff><exp>23</exp></number><unit>atoms.mol<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number></para>
	      <para>Number of atoms = <correct><number><coeff>1.14</coeff><exp>22</exp></number> atoms</correct>.</para>
	    </solution>
