      <multi-part>
	<shortcode>00zr</shortcode>
	<header>
	  <para>A learner finds some sulfuric acid solution in a bottle labelled 'dilute sulfuric acid'. He wants to determine the concentration of the sulfuric acid solution. To do this, he decides to titrate the sulfuric acid against a standard potassium hydroxide (KOH) solution.</para>
	</header>
	<entry>
	  <problem>
	    <para>What is a standard solution?</para>
	  </problem>
	  <solution>
	    <para>A standard solution is a solution that contains a precisely known concentration of a substance. This substance can then be used in titrations.</para>
	  </solution>
	  <correct/>
	</entry>
	<entry>
	  <problem>
	    <para>Calculate the mass of <chem_compound>KOH</chem_compound> which he must use to make <unit_number><number>300</number><unit>cm<sup>3</sup></unit></unit_number> of a <unit_number><number>0.2</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number> <chem_compound>KOH</chem_compound> solution.</para>
	  </problem>
	  <solution>
	    <para>V(<chem_compound>KOH</chem_compound>) = <unit_number><number>300</number><unit>cm<sup>3</sup></unit></unit_number> <latex>\times \dfrac{<number>0.001</number> {\text{ dm}}^{3}}{<number>1</number> {\text{ cm}}^{3}}</latex> = <unit_number><number>0.3</number><unit>dm<sup>3</sup></unit></unit_number></para>
	    <para><latex>\text{C} = \dfrac{\text{n}}{\text{V}}</latex>, therefore n = C x V</para>
	    <para>n(<chem_compound>KOH</chem_compound>) = <unit_number><number>0.2</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number> x <unit_number><number>0.3</number><unit>dm<sup>3</sup></unit></unit_number> = <unit_number><number>0.06</number><unit>mol</unit></unit_number></para>
	    <para>M(<chem_compound>KOH</chem_compound>) = (<number>39.1</number> + <number>16.0</number> + <number>1.01</number>) <unit>g.mol<sup>-1</sup></unit> = <unit_number><number>56.11</number><unit>g.mol<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number></para>
	    <para><latex>\text{n} = \dfrac{\text{m}}{\text{M}}</latex>, therefore m = n x M</para>
	    <para>m(<chem_compound>KOH</chem_compound>) = <unit_number><number>0.06</number><unit>mol</unit></unit_number> x <unit_number><number>56.11</number><unit>g.mol<sup>-1</sup></unit></unit_number> = <correct><unit_number><number>3.37</number><unit>g</unit></unit_number></correct></para>
	  </solution>
	</entry>
	<entry>
	  <problem>
	    <para>Calculate the pH of the <unit_number><number>0.2</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number> <chem_compound>KOH</chem_compound> solution (assume standard temperature).</para>
	  </problem>
	  <solution>
	    <para><chem_compound>KOH</chem_compound> is a very strong base and will completely dissociate in water. Therefore the concentration of <chem_compound>OH^{-}</chem_compound> ions is the same as the concentration of the solution.</para>
	    <para>pH is defined as: pH = -log<chem_compound>[H^{+}]</chem_compound></para>
	    <para>However, we can also define pOH in a similar way: pOH = -log<chem_compound>[OH^{-}]</chem_compound></para>
	    <para>The relationship between the two is: 14 = pH + pOH, therefore pH = 14 - pOH</para>
	    <para>pH = <number>14</number> - (-log<chem_compound>[OH^{-}]</chem_compound>) = <number>14</number> - (-log[<number>0.2</number>]) = <number>14</number> - <number>0.7</number> = <correct><number>13.3</number></correct></para>
	  </solution>
	</entry>
	<entry>
	  <problem>
	    <para>Write a balanced chemical equation for the reaction between <chem_compound>H_{2}SO_{4}</chem_compound> and <chem_compound>KOH</chem_compound>.</para>
	  </problem>
	  <solution>
	    <para>Sulfuric acid is a strong acid and potassium hydroxide is a strong base, therefore the equation is:</para>
	    <para><chem_compound>H_{2}SO_{4}(aq) + 2KOH(aq)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>K_{2}SO_{4}(aq) + 2H_{2}O(ℓ)</chem_compound></para>
	  </solution>
	  <correct/>
	</entry>
	<entry>
	  <problem>
	    <para>During the titration the learner finds that <unit_number><number>15</number><unit>cm<sup>3</sup></unit></unit_number> of the KOH solution neutralises <unit_number><number>20</number><unit>cm<sup>3</sup></unit></unit_number> of the <chem_compound>H_{2}SO_{4}</chem_compound> solution. Calculate the concentration of the <chem_compound>H_{2}SO_{4}</chem_compound> solution.</para>
	    <para>(IEB Paper 2, 2003)</para>
	  </problem>
	  <solution>
	    <para>V(KOH) = <unit_number><number>15</number><unit>cm<sup>3</sup></unit></unit_number> <latex>\times \dfrac{<number>0.001</number> {\text{ dm}}^{3}}{<number>1</number> {\text{ cm}}^{3}}</latex> = <unit_number><number>0.015</number><unit>dm<sup>3</sup></unit></unit_number></para>
	    <para>The number of moles of <chem_compound>KOH</chem_compound> used to neutralise the <chem_compound>H_{2}SO_{4}</chem_compound> is:</para>
	    <para>n(<chem_compound>KOH</chem_compound>) = C x V = <unit_number><number>0.2</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number> x <unit_number><number>0.015</number><unit>dm<sup>3</sup></unit></unit_number> = <unit_number><number>0.003</number><unit>mol</unit></unit_number></para>
	    <para>From the balanced equation we see that the mole ratio of <chem_compound>H_{2}SO_{4}</chem_compound> to <chem_compound>KOH</chem_compound> is <number>1</number>:<number>2</number>. There is one mole of sulfuric acid for every two moles of potassium hydroxide.</para>
	    <para>n(<chem_compound>H_{2}SO_{4}</chem_compound>) = <latex>\dfrac{<unit_number><number>0.003</number><unit>mol</unit></unit_number>}{<number>2</number>}</latex> = <unit_number><number>0.0015</number><unit>mol</unit></unit_number></para>
	    <para>V(<chem_compound>H_{2}SO_{4}</chem_compound>) = <unit_number><number>20</number><unit>cm<sup>3</sup></unit></unit_number> <latex>\times \dfrac{<number>0.001</number> {\text{ dm}}^{3}}{<number>1</number> {\text{ cm}}^{3}}</latex> = <unit_number><number>0.020</number><unit>dm<sup>3</sup></unit></unit_number></para>
	    <para>Therefore, the concentration of the sulfuric acid is:</para>
	    <para>C(<chem_compound>H_{2}SO_{4}</chem_compound>)<latex> = \dfrac{\text{n}}{\text{V}} = \dfrac{<unit_number><number>0.0015</number><unit>mol</unit></unit_number>}{<unit_number><number>0.020</number><unit>dm<sup>3</sup></unit></unit_number>}</latex> = <correct><unit_number><number>0.075</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number></correct></para>
	  </solution>
	</entry>
